You can only return an identifier

here it is true

The reason you are seeing return true; instead of a temporary identifier is due to how your isSimpleIdent() helper method is implemented at the bottom of CodeGenVisitor.java.
The Root Cause

When your visit(MethodDeclaration n, CodeGenContext ctx) evaluates the return expression, it tries to normalize it using toIdent().

toIdent calls isSimpleIdent("true"). Because "true" is composed entirely of letters, isSimpleIdent returns true. It thinks "true" is a valid variable name! Since it assumes it's already an identifier, it skips creating a temporary variable and just returns the literal string.
The Fix

You need to explicitly prevent Java keywords and literals like "true", "false", and "this" from being classified as simple variable identifiers.

Update the isSimpleIdent method at the very bottom of your CodeGenVisitor.java file to explicitly reject these keywords:
Java

    /**
     * Returns true if s is a valid Java identifier (letter/$/_ followed by
     * letter/digit/$/_ only). Used to decide whether a temp is needed.
     */
    private boolean isSimpleIdent(String s) {
        if (s == null || s.isEmpty())
            return false;

        // ADD THIS CHECK: Reject literals and keywords
        if (s.equals("true") || s.equals("false") || s.equals("this") || s.equals("null")) {
            return false;
        }

        char first = s.charAt(0);
        if (!Character.isLetter(first) && first != '_' && first != '$')
            return false;
        for (int i = 1; i < s.length(); i++) {
            char c = s.charAt(i);
            if (!Character.isLetterOrDigit(c) && c != '_' && c != '$')
                return false;
        }
        return true;
    }

Why this works

Once you add that if statement, isSimpleIdent("true") will return false.

Because it's no longer considered a simple identifier, your toIdent() method will properly generate a temporary variable for it, resulting in the correct TacoJava output:
Java

    public boolean SetRight(Tree rn) {
        boolean _t0;
        right = rn;
        _t0 = true;
        return _t0;
    }

The error required: Tree found: Object means your TacoJava compiler generated a temporary variable typed as Object (e.g., Object _t81;) and passed it into a method that strictly requires a Tree argument.

This happens because your CodeGenVisitor failed to correctly infer the return type of the expression that was passed as the argument, causing it to fall back to "Object".

The root cause is a bug in how you are inferring types for method calls (message sends).
The Bug in inferMessageSendType

If we look closely at your inferMessageSendType method in CodeGenVisitor.java:
Java

    private String inferMessageSendType(MessageSend ms, CodeGenContext ctx) {
        String methodName = ms.f2.f0.tokenImage;
        // BUG IS HERE:
        if (ctx.currentClass != null) {
            String ret = ctx.symTable.getMethodReturnType(ctx.currentClass, methodName);
            if (!"Object".equals(ret))
                return ret;
        }
        // ... fallback ...
    }

When evaluating a method call like n.GetRight(), the compiler needs to know the type of n (the receiver) to look up the method GetRight.

However, your code completely ignores the receiver (ms.f0)! Instead, it asks the symbol table to look for the method inside ctx.currentClass (the class where the code is currently executing). If you call n.GetRight() from inside your Visitor class, the compiler searches Visitor for GetRight, fails to find it, and eventually falls back to "Object".
The Fix

You need to infer the type of the receiver first, and then ask the Symbol Table to look up the method inside that specific class.

Update your inferMessageSendType method at the bottom of CodeGenVisitor.java to look like this:
Java

    /**
     * Infer the return type of a MessageSend by looking up the method
     * in the symbol table using the inferred type of the RECEIVER.
     */
    private String inferMessageSendType(MessageSend ms, CodeGenContext ctx) {
        String methodName = ms.f2.f0.tokenImage;

        // 1. Infer the type of the receiver (e.g. 'n' in 'n.GetRight()')
        String receiverType = inferPrimType(ms.f0, ctx);

        // 2. Look up the method in the receiver's class hierarchy
        if (receiverType != null && !"Object".equals(receiverType)) {
            String ret = ctx.symTable.getMethodReturnType(receiverType, methodName);
            if (!"Object".equals(ret)) {
                return ret;
            }
        }

        // 3. Fallback: Search all classes (best-effort for untyped receivers)
        for (SymbolTable.ClassInfo ci : ctx.symTable.getAllClasses().values()) {
            SymbolTable.MethodInfo mi = ci.getMethod(methodName);
            if (mi != null)
                return mi.returnType;
        }
        return "Object";
    }

Why this works

By calling inferPrimType(ms.f0, ctx), you correctly extract the type of the receiver. If the BuritoJava code says n.GetRight(), the compiler will realize n is of type "Tree".

It will then call ctx.symTable.getMethodReturnType("Tree", "GetRight"), which will successfully return "Tree". Your temporary variable will now be properly generated as Tree _t81; instead of Object _t81;, and the compilation error will go away.

