sane error

The error you are encountering (required: Tree found: Object) happens because your generated TacoJava code is creating a temporary variable for this, but typing it as Object instead of its actual class type (e.g., Tree).

Because TacoJava method calls strictly require identifiers as arguments, extracting this into a temporary variable (_t81 = this;) is correct behavior. The only bug is the type of that temporary variable (Object _t81; instead of Tree _t81;).

Here is why this is happening and how to fix it:
1. ctx.currentClass is Evaluating to "Object"

In your provided code, your inferPrimType correctly attempts to handle ThisExpression:
Java

if (choice instanceof ThisExpression)
    return ctx.currentClass != null ? ctx.currentClass : "Object";

If this is outputting Object _t81;, it means one of two things is happening:

    You have not recompiled your CodeGenVisitor.java since adding this logic, so the compiler is using an older .class file that falls back to "Object".

    ctx.currentClass is somehow resolving to null in your live environment, causing the ternary operator to default to "Object".

The Fix:
Ensure your inferPrimType method explicitly handles ThisExpression securely, and verify you are running javac CodeGenVisitor.java to compile these changes.

Replace your inferPrimType with this slightly more robust version to prevent it from ever falling through:
Java

    private String inferPrimType(PrimaryExpression n, CodeGenContext ctx) {
        Node choice = n.f0.choice;
        if (choice instanceof IntegerLiteral) return "int";
        if (choice instanceof TrueLiteral) return "boolean";
        if (choice instanceof FalseLiteral) return "boolean";

        if (choice instanceof Identifier) {
            String name = ((Identifier) choice).f0.tokenImage;
            return ctx.symTable.lookupVarType(name, ctx.currentClass, ctx.currentMethod);
        }

        // Ensure 'this' correctly grabs the current class scope
        if (choice instanceof ThisExpression) {
            if (ctx.currentClass != null) {
                return ctx.currentClass;
            }
            return "Object"; 
        }

        if (choice instanceof ArrayAllocationExpression) return "int[]";
        if (choice instanceof AllocationExpression) {
            return ((AllocationExpression) choice).f1.f0.tokenImage;
        }
        if (choice instanceof NotExpression) return "boolean";
        if (choice instanceof BracketExpression) {
            return inferExprType(((BracketExpression) choice).f1, ctx);
        }
        return "int";
    }

2. You reverted the inferMessageSendType fix

I noticed in the CodeGenVisitor.java code you provided, your inferMessageSendType is still using the buggy version that completely ignores the receiver type (e.g., ignoring n in n.GetRight()).

If you do not update this, you will immediately run into another required: Tree found: Object error as soon as you evaluate a method call on an object.

Update your inferMessageSendType (near the bottom of the file) to infer the receiver's type first:
Java

    private String inferMessageSendType(MessageSend ms, CodeGenContext ctx) {
        String methodName = ms.f2.f0.tokenImage;

        // 1. Infer the type of the receiver FIRST
        String receiverType = inferPrimType(ms.f0, ctx);

        // 2. Look up the method in that specific class
        if (receiverType != null && !"Object".equals(receiverType)) {
            String ret = ctx.symTable.getMethodReturnType(receiverType, methodName);
            if (!"Object".equals(ret)) {
                return ret;
            }
        }

        // 3. Fallback: Search all classes
        for (SymbolTable.ClassInfo ci : ctx.symTable.getAllClasses().values()) {
            SymbolTable.MethodInfo mi = ci.getMethod(methodName);
            if (mi != null)
                return mi.returnType;
        }
        return "Object";
    }

3. Verify your isSimpleIdent fix

Just to be absolutely sure, verify that your isSimpleIdent method at the very bottom of your file is successfully rejecting keywords so that TacoJava wraps them in temporaries properly. Your pasted code was missing this check. It should look like this:
Java

    private boolean isSimpleIdent(String s) {
        if (s == null || s.isEmpty()) return false;

        // Must reject these so they get extracted to temporary identifiers!
        if (s.equals("true") || s.equals("false") || s.equals("this") || s.equals("null")) {
            return false;
        }

        char first = s.charAt(0);
        if (!Character.isLetter(first) && first != '_' && first != '$') return false;
        for (int i = 1; i < s.length(); i++) {
            char c = s.charAt(i);
            if (!Character.isLetterOrDigit(c) && c != '_' && c != '$') return false;
        }
        return true;
    }

Make sure to recompile all your .java files after making these changes. Once recompiled, ctx.newTemp(type) will correctly receive "Tree" instead of "Object", and it will correctly output Tree _t81; in your final TacoJava file.

The reason you are still seeing Object _t81 = this; is due to a very subtle state bug in your CodeGenContext.java file.
The Root Cause

If you look at your CodeGenContext.java file, you have this method:
Java

  public String exitMethodScope() {
    // ... flushes buffers ...

    // Reset
    varDecls = null;
    tempDecls = null;
    bodyStmts = null;
    currentClass = null; // <-- THE BUG IS HERE
    currentMethod = null;
    indentLevel = 0;
    return sb.toString();
  }

In your CodeGenVisitor.java, currentClass is set once when visiting a ClassDeclaration. But because your exitMethodScope() sets currentClass = null at the end of every method, the context forgets what class it is in after the very first method finishes compiling.

Because accept() is the 4th method in your Tree class, ctx.currentClass has long been null by the time it gets compiled. Because it doesn't know what class it's in, your inferPrimType method falls back to Object when it sees the this keyword.
The Fix

Step 1: Update CodeGenContext.java
Remove currentClass = null; from your exitMethodScope() method so the class context survives across multiple methods.
Java

  public String exitMethodScope() {
    StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
    for (String d : varDecls)
      sb.append("    ").append(d).append("\n");
    for (String d : tempDecls)
      sb.append("    ").append(d).append("\n");
    sb.append(bodyStmts);

    // Reset
    varDecls = null;
    tempDecls = null;
    bodyStmts = null;
    // currentClass = null;  <-- REMOVE THIS LINE
    currentMethod = null;
    indentLevel = 0;
    return sb.toString();
  }

Step 2: Ensure inferPrimType is properly mapped
In CodeGenVisitor.java, double-check that your inferPrimType explicitly handles the ThisExpression like this:
Java

    private String inferPrimType(PrimaryExpression n, CodeGenContext ctx) {
        Node choice = n.f0.choice;
        // ... (other literal checks) ...

        if (choice instanceof ThisExpression) {
            // Because of the fix above, ctx.currentClass will now correctly be "Tree"
            return ctx.currentClass != null ? ctx.currentClass : "Object"; 
        }

        // ... (other checks) ...
        return "Object";
    }

Why this solves it

Once you remove that line and recompile your compiler (javac *.java), ctx.currentClass will correctly stay "Tree" for all methods inside the Tree class.

When your visitor reaches v.visit(this); inside the accept method, it will successfully infer that this has the type "Tree". It will output Tree _t81; instead of Object _t81;, and the compilation error will disappear!
